-- Asia Fuel Oil Refining Losses Widen; Gasoil Margins Increase: Oil Products
-- B y   A n n   K o h
-- 2010-11-29T06:11:42Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-29/asia-fuel-oil-refining-losses-widen-gasoil-margins-increase-oil-products.html
Asian fuel-oil refining margins
declined on speculation stockpiles in Singapore are increasing
because of rising imports from South America and the Middle
East. Gasoil’s processing profits widened.  Fuel Oil  Fuel oil’s  discount  to Dubai crude, a measure of losses
from producing the fuel, increased to $7.27 a barrel from $7.24
on Nov. 26, according to PVM Oil Associate, a brokerage.
December high-sulfur fuel oil  swaps  rose $3, or 0.6 percent, to
$494.25 a metric ton, PVM data showed.  “In the coming months, higher Western fuel oil flows to
Asia are expected which should add pressure to Asian residual
cracks,” Vienna-based JBC Energy GmbH said in a report dated
Nov. 27.  Singapore’s stockpiles of residues, or fuel oil, rose to
the highest in more than two months, data from the Ministry of
Trade and Industry showed last week. Onshore inventories gained
21 percent to 22.9 million barrels in the seven days ended Nov.
24 from a week earlier, the data showed.  Middle Distillates  Gasoil’s  premium  to Dubai crude, or the crack spread,
widened to $13.34 a barrel from $12.84 on Nov. 26, according to
PVM. December  swaps for gasoil , or diesel, gained $1, or 1.1
percent, to $96.65 a barrel.  Jet fuel ’s premium to gasoil was unchanged at $1.55 barrel,
the biggest since January. A wider spread, or regrade, indicates
rising profit from producing the aviation fuel compared with
diesel.  Naphtha  Japan’s benchmark open-specification naphtha forward
contracts for second-half January delivery were bid at $801.75 a
ton against offers at $804.75, according to Ginga Petroleum
Singapore Pte, a brokerage. First-half February cargoes were bid
at $797.50 a ton compared with offers at $800.50, data from
Ginga Petroleum showed.  Prices  for mid-January to mid-February delivery rose $2.13,
or 0.3 percent, to $801.13 a ton on Nov. 26, according to data
compiled by Bloomberg.  Japan naphtha’s difference to Brent crude, or the crack
spread, dropped to $152.35 a ton from $158.93 at the end of
Asian trading last week, according to Bloomberg calculations.  To contact the reporter on this story:
